@NODE "Relabel" "Part 11 - The RENAME & RELABEL Commands - RELABEL"

@{B}@{U}The RELABEL Command@{UB}@{UU}

@{B}Location@{UB}     - "c" directory - All versions

@{B}Purpose@{UB}      - To change the name of a volume
               (hard drive partition or floppy disk.)

@{B}Availability@{UB} - All AmigaDOS Versions

This command is used only on disks and hard drive partitions. To rename
directories and files you use the @{"RENAME" LINK "Rename"} command.

This command can be used in one of these forms, all of which do the same
things:-

  RELABEL DRIVE name NAME NewName

  RELABEL name NewName

The keywords DRIVE and NAME can be omitted as illustrated in the second
line above.

The names must comply with the @{"rules for naming files and directories" LINK "ADB:Parts_01-10/03.Dirs_Files_Paths/Naming"}.

Examples are:

  RELABEL MyDisk: Games

  RELABEL df1: MyDisk

In the DRIVE position, you can put the name of the volume or the name
of the drive that it is in. In either case it must be followed by a
colon.

If you use a drive name (e.g. df1:) then you @{B}must be careful@{UB} to ensure
that the correct disk is in the drive.

In the NAME position you put the new name but do @{B}not@{UB} use a colon after it!

@{B}WARNING@{UB} - If you use RELABEL on an @{"assigned directory" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/LogicalDevices"} name then the
volume name holding the assigned directory will be relabelled.

For example, the assigned directory "C:" is on the disk you booted up from.
Let's assume that you booted up from your boot disk or hard drive partition
that is named "Workbench3.1".

The "C:" assignment is therefore to:-

  Workbench3.1:C

If you use:-

  > RELABEL C: Garbage

then you will find that you have relabelled your Workbench3.1 disk to
"Garbage"!!!


